optical neural networks (onns) have been developed to accelerate deep learning tasks due to their potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost. these networks typically use light amplitudes at the input and output, but they ignore the light phases. to address this issue, we propose a framework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating input image data into both the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. we redesign the input and output parts of the onn to make full use of both amplitude and phase information, and introduce mutual learning across different onn structures to maintain the accuracy. our experimental results demonstrate that the proposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns while maintaining accuracy within an acceptable range. for example, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.

On-chip optical neural networks (ONNs) have attracted significant attention due to their high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost. To further improve their efficiency, we propose a framework called OplixNet to compress the areas of ONNs by modulating input image data into both the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. We redesigned the input and output parts of the ONN to make full use of both amplitude and phase information, and introduced mutual learning across different ONN structures to maintain accuracy. Our experimental results demonstrate that the proposed framework significantly reduces the areas of ONNs while maintaining accuracy within an acceptable range. For example, a 0.33% accuracy decrease is observed on FCNN and a 2.38% accuracy decrease is observed on ResNet-32.

We have created a framework called OplixNet, which aims to improve the efficiency of optical neural networks (ONNs) by compressing their areas. To achieve this, we modulate the input image data into both the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. We redesigned the input and output parts of the ONN to utilize both amplitude and phase information, and introduced mutual learning across different ONN structures to maintain accuracy. Our experimental results show that the proposed framework significantly reduces the areas of ONNs while maintaining accuracy within an acceptable range. For example, when applied to a fully connected neural network (FCNN), the accuracy decreases by only 0.33%, while for a ResNet-32 architecture, the accuracy decrease is 2.38%.
